5/5  rDev +12.1%look: 5 | smell: 5 | taste: 5 | feel: 5 |  overall: 5Had on tap in a tulip glass while at the Surly Beer Hall. What an amazing West Coast Style IPA.  Wonderful tropical fruit, especially grapefruit, hits your nose instantly.  On the palate it is extremely well balanced with juicy citrus peel, grapefruit and hints of pine resin.  It packs a nice bitter punch on the end but nothing overwhelming.  The finish is extremely long and smooth.  This is one of those IPA's that sets the bar high and keeps you coming back for more time and time again.  Full marks for this amazing brew. 527 charactersDrinkzumbeer, Jan 21, 2016
4.47/5  rDev +0.2%look: 5 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.516oz pint served on draught at Monk's Pub in Chicago, poured into a shaker pint glass, reviewed from Tasting Journal.
The beer pours a very hazy and cloudy copper color, apricot and gold hues with a finger of taut, white, foamy head, great retention and wonderful lace. The aroma is fantastic, bursting with hops, dank, resinous, but also bright and floral, loads of citrus, floral, juicy, piney with crisp cereal grains offering a bit of sweetness. The flavors are great, just a massive hop profile, tons of pine, dank grassiness, wildflower, citrus peel, juicy tropical fruits, really snappy and crisp, assertively bitter to boot with a great bite. The mouthfeel is great, coating, crisp, lively, medium body, exceptionally dry, big biting finish that isn't unwelcome.
Verdict: A damn fine IPA from Surly and Amager Bryghus. Exploding with hops, juicy, crisp, intensely flavorful and fantastically bitter without losing any flavor. Easily one of my new favorite IPAs and one I hope to see in rotation as frequently as possible. 1,031 characterskevanb, Jan 21, 2016
