4.38/5  rDev -1.8%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.25So I had heard rave reviews about this beer and decided to do something that i'd promise myself not to do again: trade for.  Luckily, the person I traded with is among the best traders out there (literally, what a great guy!). 
A: Hazy dark orange, apricot like in color. Has a golden orange color when held up to the light with half of a one finger white, foamy head that very quickly dissipates into nothing (really, this beer lacks substantial carbonation).
S: Dank! Super dank combined with a fresh hop punch to your nostrils. You really have to sniff hard to detect anything else. I noticed a hint of peach, some pine and perhaps pineapple and mango. There is a distinct sweetness that is detected besides the very apparent dankness.
T: Very similar to the nose. The sticky hop oil like dankness is the first thing I taste followed by a tropical citrus like sweetness.
M: Mild to zero carbonation wise, thin-medium mouthfeel, hops are prickly to the tongue with a substantial dry, bitter finish. The stickiness seems to cling to the mouth upon finishing a sip.
O: Very glad I can put the rumors to bed! Sorry folks, this beer is good, but more of a "Lupulin River" by Knee Deep Brewing (CA) good. This is not on the level of any New England IPA that i've had (8 of the 9 top NE IPA's). 1,290 charactersMA_hops, Aug 28, 2015
4.72/5  rDev +5.8%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.7516 oz can poured into nonic pint dated 7/23
A: Dirty murky amber very small head 
S: Peaches, cantaloupe, pineapple with a very little bready nose on the end
T: very juicy lots of that nice harsh pineapple giving way to light cantaloupe and peachy stone fruit with a nice light crackery malt backbone 
M: light with just a shade of syrupiness low carbonation 
O: This beer is fantastic if you want a fruit explosion from your IPAs its so juicy and just a very light cracker malt backbone if you ever had Swish by Bissell Brothers or Epiphany from Foundation Brewing you are going to absolutely love this beer. 614 charactersSomethingClever, Aug 28, 2015
4.05/5  rDev -9.2%look: 3.75 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4RickyBfromCT, Aug 28, 2015
4.5/5  rDev +0.9%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5Poured from a glorious pounder can into a Teku glass.
L: Pours a dark orangy yellow that is a breathtaking golden orange when held to the light. There was about a finger or 2 of white head that disappeared into a ring around the glass.
S: Smells pretty damn dank. Mosaic and Citra hops are an incredible combination and I've been waiting for a brewery to do this. Strong orange, peach, and papaya notes are what I smell immediately. Some grapefruit also comes through in addition to a little bit of pine and even some mango. Man the depth of smell is wonderful.
T: Pun intended, this is a bit abrasive, but not really (if that makes sense.) The taste follows the nose pretty well. The zesty orange and peach come through immediately with the grapefruit, mango and papaya notes coming through shortly after. This is damn good. There is a nice amount of bitterness, but it's not overbearing at all.
F: This has a supreme amount of flavor for a beer that is 7.2%. The carbonation is prickly, but it works with the beer very well. The alcohol is not present, but I don't think I could have more of one of these in a sitting. I can't say that for other IPAs that even go up to 8%.
Overall: This is a really nice beer. I am quite spoiled with all the wonderful IPAs that are available to me in New England, but I am glad that I was able to see what Minnesota has to offer. The bitterness is nice, as well as the flavor. I am a sucker for citra and mosaic hops and to see them combined in an IPA is something that I've been waiting for. This is my first beer from Surly and I'd love to try some other IPAs that they have. Especially if they're as good as this one. 1,662 charactersRichD, Aug 27, 2015
