4.07/5  rDev -8.7%look: 4 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 3.5 |  overall: 4I remember having this at the brewery this last summer, and being surprised by the fact that I did not enjoy it that much considering that it is one of Minnesota's highest rated beers. As such, I've been meaning to have the Axe Man again for quite some time, just to see whether my opinion of it would increase if I had it during different circumstances. 
Pours a small and relatively bubbly head. The body has a hazy golden color, with little visible carbonation. 
Smells of citra-laden hops, with some floral undertones. I also got quite a large degree of fruit in the nose, both of exotic fruits, but also of apple. 
Quite a nuanced taste, with both piney and bitter hops, and the sweetness and juiciness of the exotic fruits. The taste also features a grassy and dank aftertaste. The bitterness of the hops become more prominent as it warms. Carbonation is delightfully light, and mouthfeel is medium-light, and quite dry. Even though, I tend to prefer my IPA's to be juicier. 
I can really appreciate this beer, while also conceding that this is not for me. The admittedly moderate, yet present bitterness is above what I would consider optimal. Furthermore, and probably more importantly, its dry nature aggravated the bitterness. It is undoubtedly a case of me not seeing eye-to-eye with the vision however, as my problem with Todd is more the case of me not appreciating what this beer is going for, rather than it not being a phenomenal brew. As made evident by the fact that I feel apologetic for 'only' giving this a 4.07. 1,537 charactersWer34truh, Aug 23, 2015
4.61/5  rDev +3.4%look: 4 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.57/31/15 canning date. 16 oz. can.
Pours a cloudy dark orange color with about a finger of bright white head. Some yeast floaties in the beer.
Smells of extremely dank hops. One of the dankest beers I've ever smelled. Also get pineapple, mango, papaya, orange juice, and grapefruit. All the fruits are very sweet and juicy. Also get a bit of pine and chive.
Taste is a complex assortment of juicy tropical and citrus fruits and dankness. Some of that chive makes an appearance as well. A wonderful dry finish with a significant citrus pith and pine resin bitterness. 
Medium body. Slightly crisp and creamy. No carbonation issues here.
This beer is extremely hyped up and for the most part, it lives up to the hype. Really shows what intensity and complexity Citra and Mosaic can have. One of the better, if not the best, single IPA's coming out of the Midwest right now. 875 charactersbrewskis, Aug 23, 2015
