4.52/5  rDev +1.3%look: 3.75 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.75I'm so glad a bought a lot of this smashing hop juice...review based on a pour into my standard IPA glass from a batch canned 7/21/15.
Pours a fairly opaque amber. Lacing is spotty, and not very robust. Head is standard eggshell white without much heft. It looks inviting enough, but I think the least impressive element of TTAM.
Nose has such a fresh, buzzing green overlay to the fruit basket of papaya, mango, pineapple, and citrus. The hint of scallion is just right. Tropical hop bitterness jumps out of the glass. It almost pulls my tongue in.
Opens with bright lemon-led citrus, papaya and mango laced with its characteristic unripe pine. Then that dry, pine hop bitterness slide in behind a firm malt note that re-introduces sweetness by way of bread yeast--brilliant! A touch of resin mixed with a grassiness and more fruit in the end and finish. Hop oils create more of that synesthete fun, bridging flavor and feel and bouquet all at once.
The nearly light body is a surprising counterpoint to the heavy complexity of a DIPA. Smooth and almost thirst-quenching; so easy to drink more and more.  Finishes dry and filmy with a long, lingering, balanced astringency. The feel just doesn't encourage savoring...
I've heard this beast is the best DIPA in the Midwest. Haven't been here long, but so far, I must agree. On tap, it was too pithy and sharply acidic right up front in a way that wrecked the whole experience. But in the can, it's a work of art. Like all great creations holding so much vibrant complexity, when it's just a bit off, the problematic sharp edges are unpleasant, but when it's all in balance, it's heavenly. 1,643 characters1sophrosyne1, Aug 15, 2015
